In article <252t1j$ih4@news.u.washington.edu>,
Tim Smith <tzs@hardy.u.washington.edu> wrote:
>I've seen procedures for logically flipping a coin by phone.  They tend
>to be complicated.  

How about this -- given secure hash function HASH:

	A&B each choose a random number R(A), R(B);

	A&B reveal to each other HASH(R(A)) and HASH(R(B))

	A&B now reveal R(A) and R(B) to each other -- note they 
	cannot now deny what R(A) and R(B) where, because they
	couldn't make R(A)' and R(B)' such that 
		HASH(R(X)) == HASH(R(X)')

	The "coin" is "heads" if (R(A)^R(B))&01 == 1, tails otherwise.
